1
00:00:00,008 --> 00:00:00,792
Okay.

2
00:00:00,792 --> 00:00:01,875
Imagine this.

3
00:00:01,875 --> 00:00:05,277
It's January 21st, 1793.

4
00:00:05,277 --> 00:00:08,478
France is 4 years into a revolution.

5
00:00:08,478 --> 00:00:10,179
The monarchy has collapsed.

6
00:00:10,179 --> 00:00:12,330
The church has been dismantled.

7
00:00:12,330 --> 00:00:15,181
The old aristocratic order, gone.

8
00:00:15,181 --> 00:00:17,066
The country is trying to build itself

9
00:00:17,066 --> 00:00:19,783
from scratch, and nobody is quite sure

10
00:00:19,783 --> 00:00:20,951
it's going to work.

11
00:00:20,951 --> 00:00:21,784
You're in Paris,

12
00:00:21,784 --> 00:00:23,752
sitting in the National Convention,

13
00:00:23,752 --> 00:00:26,186
the new revolutionary parliament,

14
00:00:26,186 --> 00:00:27,904
and a vote is being taken.

15
00:00:27,904 --> 00:00:29,288
Should the King of France

16
00:00:29,288 --> 00:00:30,505
be put to death?

17
00:00:30,505 --> 00:00:31,605
now, the room

18
00:00:31,605 --> 00:00:35,541
is full of politicians, lawyers, revolutionaries,

19
00:00:35,541 --> 00:00:37,925
but sitting amongst them, voting,

20
00:00:37,925 --> 00:00:40,526
is a painter, the most famous painter

21
00:00:40,526 --> 00:00:41,627
in France, a man

22
00:00:41,627 --> 00:00:43,961
whose paintings hang in the Louvre,

23
00:00:43,961 --> 00:00:45,595
whose work has made grown men

24
00:00:45,595 --> 00:00:47,546
weep in public.

25
00:00:47,546 --> 00:00:49,930
And when his name is called,

26
00:00:49,930 --> 00:00:51,047
he stands up,

27
00:00:51,047 --> 00:00:53,248
and he votes yes.

28
00:00:53,248 --> 00:00:55,349
He votes to kill the king.

29
00:00:55,349 --> 00:00:57,183
His name was Jacques-Louis David,

30
00:00:57,183 --> 00:00:59,418
and that vote, a painter

31
00:00:59,418 --> 00:01:00,852
voting on the life of a king,

32
00:01:00,852 --> 00:01:03,036
would define everything that came after,

33
00:01:03,036 --> 00:01:04,537
For better and for worse.

34
00:01:04,537 --> 00:01:06,621
But to understand how he got there,

35
00:01:06,621 --> 00:01:08,439
we first need to ask:

36
00:01:08,439 --> 00:01:10,389
How does a painter ends up

37
00:01:10,389 --> 00:01:11,823
with that kind of power?

38
00:01:11,823 --> 00:01:13,191
To understand that, we need

39
00:01:13,191 --> 00:01:15,542
to go way back before David,

40
00:01:15,542 --> 00:01:18,026
before the revolution, back to a time

41
00:01:18,026 --> 00:01:20,527
when French art looked very different.

42
00:01:20,527 --> 00:01:20,811
how do

43
00:01:20,811 --> 00:01:22,278
you pronounce the name?

44
00:01:22,278 --> 00:01:24,913
Jean-Honoré Fragonard.

45
00:01:24,913 --> 00:01:26,697
Jean-Honoré Fra-Fragonard.

46
00:01:26,697 --> 00:01:28,581
Look at this painting, The Swing

47
00:01:28,581 --> 00:01:31,699
by Jean-Honoré Fragonard, 1767.

48
00:01:31,699 --> 00:01:33,266
A woman swings her shoe,

49
00:01:33,266 --> 00:01:34,934
flying toward the little angel

50
00:01:34,934 --> 00:01:36,484
who gestures shh

51
00:01:36,484 --> 00:01:38,335
to show a secret is unfolding.

52
00:01:38,335 --> 00:01:39,686
A man hides in the bushes,

53
00:01:39,686 --> 00:01:41,236
looking up her skirt

54
00:01:41,236 --> 00:01:44,004
while the older man pushes the swing,

55
00:01:44,004 --> 00:01:45,955
unaware of what's happening.

56
00:01:45,955 --> 00:01:48,957
This painting is witty, flirtatious,

57
00:01:48,957 --> 00:01:50,824
and entirely wrapped up

58
00:01:50,824 --> 00:01:52,141
in the private pleasures

59
00:01:52,141 --> 00:01:53,242
of the ruling class.

60
00:01:53,242 --> 00:01:56,176
And the French aristocracy loved this stuff.

61
00:01:56,176 --> 00:01:57,044
This was the art

62
00:01:57,044 --> 00:01:58,227
of the ruling class.

63
00:01:58,227 --> 00:02:00,112
Rococo, they called it. Light,

64
00:02:00,112 --> 00:02:01,979
decorative, charming, sexy.

65
00:02:01,979 --> 00:02:03,196
Say Boucher.

66
00:02:03,196 --> 00:02:05,497
Painters like Boucher and Fragonard

67
00:02:05,497 --> 00:02:08,132
made a fortune painting exactly this.

68
00:02:08,132 --> 00:02:10,533
Beautiful people doing beautiful things

69
00:02:10,533 --> 00:02:11,817
in beautiful gardens.

70
00:02:11,817 --> 00:02:15,252
But by the 1760s,

71
00:02:15,252 --> 00:02:17,119
not everyone was charmed.

72
00:02:17,119 --> 00:02:18,970
The critic Denis Diderot,

73
00:02:18,970 --> 00:02:21,338
one of the sharpest minds in France,

74
00:02:21,338 --> 00:02:23,355
looked at Boucher's paintings

75
00:02:23,355 --> 00:02:23,989
and wrote.

76
00:02:23,989 --> 00:02:26,090
What colors, what variety,

77
00:02:26,090 --> 00:02:28,407
what a wealth of objects and ideas.

78
00:02:28,407 --> 00:02:31,459
This man has everything except truth.

79
00:02:31,459 --> 00:02:32,793
Except truth.

80
00:02:32,793 --> 00:02:34,127
That's the key word,

81
00:02:34,127 --> 00:02:37,912
because underneath all that silk and powder,

82
00:02:37,912 --> 00:02:41,763
France was rottingThe monarchy was broke,

83
00:02:41,763 --> 00:02:44,715
the peasants were starving, and the art,

84
00:02:44,715 --> 00:02:48,216
the officials celebrated expensive art

85
00:02:48,216 --> 00:02:50,901
was paintings of aristocrats on swings.

86
00:02:50,901 --> 00:02:52,018
It couldn't last.

87
00:02:52,018 --> 00:02:54,419
And right around this time something happened

88
00:02:54,419 --> 00:02:57,187
that changed the direction of European culture.

89
00:02:57,187 --> 00:02:58,654
They dug up Pompeii.

90
00:02:58,654 --> 00:03:01,906
well, first Herculaneum in 1730

91
00:03:01,906 --> 00:03:05,341
8, then Pompeii in 1740 8.

92
00:03:05,341 --> 00:03:07,592
2 entire Roman cities

93
00:03:07,592 --> 00:03:08,959
buried by a volcano

94
00:03:08,959 --> 00:03:12,777
in 70 9 AD, suddenly visible again.

95
00:03:12,777 --> 00:03:15,512
And it wasn't just columns

96
00:03:15,512 --> 00:03:18,263
and statues, it was everything.

97
00:03:18,263 --> 00:03:20,147
Houses, wall paintings,

98
00:03:20,147 --> 00:03:23,182
furniture, graffiti, bread still in the ovens.

99
00:03:23,182 --> 00:03:26,300
An entire civilization frozen in time.

100
00:03:26,300 --> 00:03:27,601
And among the educated,

101
00:03:27,601 --> 00:03:29,635
wealthy classes of Europe, this sparked

102
00:03:29,635 --> 00:03:32,203
a kind of ancient world mania.

103
00:03:32,203 --> 00:03:34,587
Greek furniture, Roman architecture,

104
00:03:34,587 --> 00:03:35,988
cl-classical hairstyles.

105
00:03:35,988 --> 00:03:38,389
If you were a wealthy young man,

106
00:03:38,389 --> 00:03:40,089
you went on the Grand Tour.

107
00:03:40,089 --> 00:03:41,490
You traveled to Rome,

108
00:03:41,490 --> 00:03:43,524
you sketched the ruins, you came back,

109
00:03:43,524 --> 00:03:45,175
and you told everyone

110
00:03:45,175 --> 00:03:46,842
how cultured you were.

111
00:03:46,842 --> 00:03:49,494
It was the 18th century version

112
00:03:49,494 --> 00:03:50,544
of studying abroad

113
00:03:50,544 --> 00:03:52,762
and making it your whole personality

114
00:03:52,762 --> 00:03:55,129
But the person who turned this obsession

115
00:03:55,129 --> 00:03:57,180
into a complete theory, the person

116
00:03:57,180 --> 00:03:59,615
who gave the educated classes of Europe

117
00:03:59,615 --> 00:04:02,149
a framework for why ancient Greece

118
00:04:02,149 --> 00:04:04,267
was the peak of human achievement,

119
00:04:04,267 --> 00:04:05,617
was a man who never

120
00:04:05,617 --> 00:04:07,452
painted a single painting.

121
00:04:07,452 --> 00:04:10,019
Not a painter, not an architect,

122
00:04:10,019 --> 00:04:11,904
a writer, a critic.

123
00:04:11,904 --> 00:04:14,605
His name was John Joachim Winckelmann.

124
00:04:14,605 --> 00:04:18,040
Winckelmann was born in 1717 in Prussia

125
00:04:18,040 --> 00:04:20,941
His father was a shoemaker, dirt

126
00:04:20,941 --> 00:04:23,609
poor, but the kid was brilliant.

127
00:04:23,609 --> 00:04:25,543
Taught himself Greek and Latin,

128
00:04:25,543 --> 00:04:26,760
worked as a school teacher

129
00:04:26,760 --> 00:04:28,694
and a librarian just to survive,

130
00:04:28,694 --> 00:04:31,896
and in 1755, he published a book

131
00:04:31,896 --> 00:04:33,363
that changed everything.

132
00:04:33,363 --> 00:04:34,547
It was called Thoughts

133
00:04:34,547 --> 00:04:36,481
on the Imitation of Greek Works

134
00:04:36,481 --> 00:04:38,916
in Painting and Sculpture, and in it,

135
00:04:38,916 --> 00:04:40,666
he made the claim that would echo

136
00:04:40,666 --> 00:04:42,601
for the next hundred years.

137
00:04:42,601 --> 00:04:44,752
He said that the defining quality

138
00:04:44,752 --> 00:04:45,952
of Greek art was...

139
00:04:45,952 --> 00:04:48,770
noble simplicity and quiet grandeur.

140
00:04:48,770 --> 00:04:50,121
5 words.

141
00:04:50,121 --> 00:04:51,288
That's it.

142
00:04:51,288 --> 00:04:53,105
5 words that defined

143
00:04:53,105 --> 00:04:55,640
an entire century of art.

144
00:04:55,640 --> 00:04:57,207
What did he mean?

145
00:04:57,207 --> 00:04:59,325
He meant that great art

146
00:04:59,325 --> 00:05:02,226
should be calm, restrained, balanced.

147
00:05:02,226 --> 00:05:05,094
Not screaming, no drama, no excess.

148
00:05:05,094 --> 00:05:07,012
Think of a Greek statue.

149
00:05:07,012 --> 00:05:09,496
Perfect proportions, calm expression,

150
00:05:09,496 --> 00:05:13,048
idealized body, pure white marble.

151
00:05:13,048 --> 00:05:16,282
That, Winckelmann said, was the peak.

152
00:05:16,282 --> 00:05:18,383
Everything else was step down.

153
00:05:18,383 --> 00:05:19,901
one small problem

154
00:05:19,901 --> 00:05:22,902
with this, the ancient Greeks

155
00:05:22,902 --> 00:05:26,437
did not make pure white marble statues.

156
00:05:26,437 --> 00:05:28,855
Their statues were painted

157
00:05:28,855 --> 00:05:31,739
vivid, garnished colors, bright red lips,

158
00:05:31,739 --> 00:05:33,673
blue eyes, yellow hair.

159
00:05:33,673 --> 00:05:35,057
We only know this now

160
00:05:35,057 --> 00:05:36,791
from chemical analysis

161
00:05:36,791 --> 00:05:39,509
and faint traces of pigment.

162
00:05:39,509 --> 00:05:41,344
Winckelmann had no idea.

163
00:05:41,344 --> 00:05:43,978
He built an entire aesthetic philosophy

164
00:05:43,978 --> 00:05:45,545
around the wrong thing.

165
00:05:45,545 --> 00:05:48,964
His idea of noble simplicity

166
00:05:48,964 --> 00:05:51,048
was, at least in part,

167
00:05:51,048 --> 00:05:53,466
the result of 2,000 years

168
00:05:53,466 --> 00:05:56,667
of paint wearing off, which is

169
00:05:56,667 --> 00:05:58,068
either a great argument

170
00:05:58,068 --> 00:06:00,869
for the power of an idea

171
00:06:00,869 --> 00:06:02,903
or a cautionary tale

172
00:06:02,903 --> 00:06:05,454
about inventing a perfect past

173
00:06:05,454 --> 00:06:08,489
to criticize an imperfect present.

174
00:06:08,489 --> 00:06:10,323
He moved to Rome, got access

175
00:06:10,323 --> 00:06:13,091
to the greatest collections of ancient art

176
00:06:13,091 --> 00:06:16,259
in the world, and in 1764

177
00:06:16,259 --> 00:06:19,594
published History of the Art of Antiquity,

178
00:06:19,594 --> 00:06:23,346
which transformed the discipline of art history.

179
00:06:23,346 --> 00:06:26,364
People had written about individual artists

180
00:06:26,364 --> 00:06:31,099
before, but Winckelmann organized everything around styles

181
00:06:31,099 --> 00:06:33,600
and periods, tracing the rise and fall

182
00:06:33,600 --> 00:06:36,451
of entire civilizations through their art.

183
00:06:36,451 --> 00:06:39,253
That framework, we still use it today

184
00:06:39,253 --> 00:06:40,370
Now here's the thing

185
00:06:40,370 --> 00:06:41,837
and this is important

186
00:06:41,837 --> 00:06:45,005
Winckelmann never went to Greece.

187
00:06:45,005 --> 00:06:47,856
His entire philosophy of Greek art

188
00:06:47,856 --> 00:06:50,007
was based on Roman copies.

189
00:06:50,007 --> 00:06:52,258
He was building a fantasy of Greece

190
00:06:52,258 --> 00:06:55,960
from secondhand evidence, and he did it

191
00:06:55,960 --> 00:06:59,678
so convincingly that everyone believed him.

192
00:06:59,678 --> 00:07:02,630
He was murdered in 1760 8

193
00:07:02,630 --> 00:07:03,647
in Trieste

194
00:07:03,647 --> 00:07:05,531
at the age of 50,

195
00:07:05,531 --> 00:07:07,082
stabbed by a man he'd met

196
00:07:07,082 --> 00:07:08,015
in an inn

197
00:07:08,015 --> 00:07:11,267
The circumstances suggest a sexual encounter

198
00:07:11,267 --> 00:07:12,701
gone wrong.

199
00:07:12,701 --> 00:07:15,786
Winckelmann's letters express intense romantic feelings

200
00:07:15,786 --> 00:07:17,103
toward young men,

201
00:07:17,103 --> 00:07:20,238
and most scholars read him as gay.

202
00:07:20,238 --> 00:07:21,988
Though, as with so

203
00:07:21,988 --> 00:07:23,823
much of his life, certainty

204
00:07:23,823 --> 00:07:24,906
is hard to come by.

205
00:07:24,906 --> 00:07:26,007
What we can say

206
00:07:26,007 --> 00:07:27,841
is it adds another layer

207
00:07:27,841 --> 00:07:29,909
to his lifelong idealization

208
00:07:29,909 --> 00:07:31,092
of the male Greek body.

209
00:07:31,092 --> 00:07:32,493
What matters for us is

210
00:07:32,493 --> 00:07:35,861
this, Winckelmann created the idea.

211
00:07:35,861 --> 00:07:38,712
He built the intellectual framework.

212
00:07:38,712 --> 00:07:40,513
Now, someone needed

213
00:07:40,513 --> 00:07:42,014
to turn it into paintings.

214
00:07:42,014 --> 00:07:43,081
but first you need

215
00:07:43,081 --> 00:07:44,648
to understand how the art

216
00:07:44,648 --> 00:07:48,550
world actually worked in 17th century France,

217
00:07:48,550 --> 00:07:50,951
because it was a system,

218
00:07:50,951 --> 00:07:54,570
rigid, hierarchical, and brutally competitive.

219
00:07:54,570 --> 00:07:56,070
There was one exhibition

220
00:07:56,070 --> 00:07:58,271
that mattered above all others,

221
00:07:58,271 --> 00:08:01,006
the Salon run by the Académie Royale,

222
00:08:01,006 --> 00:08:02,256
held at the Louvre.

223
00:08:02,256 --> 00:08:04,324
If you got into the Salon,

224
00:08:04,324 --> 00:08:05,658
you had a career.

225
00:08:05,658 --> 00:08:08,609
There were other patrons, other venues,

226
00:08:08,609 --> 00:08:11,877
but nothing with the Salon's reach, prestige,

227
00:08:11,877 --> 00:08:13,094
or power.

228
00:08:13,094 --> 00:08:15,412
To be excluded from the Salon

229
00:08:15,412 --> 00:08:16,746
was to be invisible.

230
00:08:16,746 --> 00:08:17,997
And within the salon

231
00:08:17,997 --> 00:08:19,764
there was a strict hierarchy

232
00:08:19,764 --> 00:08:21,948
of what you were allowed to paint.

233
00:08:21,948 --> 00:08:25,333
At the top, history paintings, scenes

234
00:08:25,333 --> 00:08:27,401
from the Bible, from mythology,

235
00:08:27,401 --> 00:08:28,735
from ancient history,

236
00:08:28,735 --> 00:08:30,652
the noblest form of art.

237
00:08:30,652 --> 00:08:32,853
And at the very bottom, still life.

238
00:08:32,853 --> 00:08:34,471
This hierarchy matters.

239
00:08:34,471 --> 00:08:37,455
It explains everything about what's coming.

240
00:08:37,455 --> 00:08:38,839
It explains why

241
00:08:38,839 --> 00:08:40,723
David painted Greek heroes.

242
00:08:40,723 --> 00:08:41,440
The other thing

243
00:08:41,440 --> 00:08:42,441
you need to know about

244
00:08:42,441 --> 00:08:44,008
is the Prix de Rome,

245
00:08:44,008 --> 00:08:45,709
the most prestigious prize

246
00:08:45,709 --> 00:08:47,226
a young artist could win.

247
00:08:47,226 --> 00:08:48,327
you win the Prix de Rome,

248
00:08:48,327 --> 00:08:49,761
you get a funded trip

249
00:08:49,761 --> 00:08:52,012
to the French Academy in Rome.

250
00:08:52,012 --> 00:08:53,863
Years of studying the masters,

251
00:08:53,863 --> 00:08:55,430
the ruins, the sculpture.

252
00:08:55,430 --> 00:08:58,031
And a young painter named Jacques-Louis David

253
00:08:58,031 --> 00:09:00,949
wanted it more than everything.

254
00:09:00,949 --> 00:09:03,700
He failed 3 times.

255
00:09:03,708 --> 00:09:06,526
David was born in Paris, 1748.

256
00:09:06,526 --> 00:09:08,543
His father was killed in a duel

257
00:09:08,543 --> 00:09:10,027
when David was very young,

258
00:09:10,027 --> 00:09:12,679
so already we're starting with violence.

259
00:09:12,679 --> 00:09:15,046
Dead parent before age 10.

260
00:09:15,046 --> 00:09:17,764
Every great origin story has one.

261
00:09:17,764 --> 00:09:19,865
He was raised by well-off uncles

262
00:09:19,865 --> 00:09:21,783
who wanted him to be an architect.

263
00:09:21,783 --> 00:09:23,400
He wanted to paint.

264
00:09:23,400 --> 00:09:23,967
he studied

265
00:09:23,967 --> 00:09:26,618
under a painter named Joseph Marie Vien,

266
00:09:26,618 --> 00:09:26,735
and

267
00:09:26,735 --> 00:09:28,619
he entered the Prix de Rome competition

268
00:09:28,619 --> 00:09:31,637
multiple times through the early 1770s.

269
00:09:31,637 --> 00:09:32,654
He lost.

270
00:09:32,654 --> 00:09:34,688
He entered again, lost again.

271
00:09:34,688 --> 00:09:37,290
He entered a third time, lost again.

272
00:09:37,290 --> 00:09:39,674
And repeated failure broke him.

273
00:09:39,674 --> 00:09:42,092
According to some biographical accounts,

274
00:09:42,092 --> 00:09:44,109
David locked himself in his room

275
00:09:44,109 --> 00:09:45,310
and refused to eat,

276
00:09:45,310 --> 00:09:48,028
convinced his life was over.

277
00:09:48,028 --> 00:09:49,612
The details are murky

278
00:09:49,612 --> 00:09:53,030
and probably exaggerated by later admirers,

279
00:09:53,030 --> 00:09:55,581
but the despair was real.

280
00:09:55,581 --> 00:09:57,199
he was in his mid twenties,

281
00:09:57,199 --> 00:09:59,600
and the one path he staked everything

282
00:09:59,600 --> 00:10:02,167
on kept closing in his face.

283
00:10:02,167 --> 00:10:04,719
He entered again in 1774.

284
00:10:04,719 --> 00:10:06,236
He didn't win.

285
00:10:06,236 --> 00:10:07,303
Just kidding.

286
00:10:07,303 --> 00:10:09,487
He finally got it.

287
00:10:09,487 --> 00:10:12,322
He went to Rome and everything changed.

288
00:10:12,322 --> 00:10:13,489
He arrived in Rome,

289
00:10:13,489 --> 00:10:16,791
and at first wasn't very impressed,

290
00:10:16,791 --> 00:10:18,825
struggling to find his direction.

291
00:10:18,825 --> 00:10:21,526
But soon, the ideas he read about,

292
00:10:21,526 --> 00:10:23,794
especially those of Winckelmann,

293
00:10:23,794 --> 00:10:25,645
the art critic, came to life

294
00:10:25,645 --> 00:10:26,728
in front of him.

295
00:10:26,728 --> 00:10:29,296
He studied ancient sculptures, Raphael

296
00:10:29,296 --> 00:10:30,980
and artists like Caravaggio,

297
00:10:30,980 --> 00:10:33,315
spending 5 years learning

298
00:10:33,315 --> 00:10:35,316
and absorbing the art around him.

299
00:10:35,316 --> 00:10:37,016
And when he came back to Paris,

300
00:10:37,016 --> 00:10:39,517
he was a completely different painter.

301
00:10:39,517 --> 00:10:41,352
The loose, colorful style

302
00:10:41,352 --> 00:10:43,636
of his early work was gone.

303
00:10:43,636 --> 00:10:46,487
In its place, moral seriousness,

304
00:10:46,487 --> 00:10:49,939
clean lines, rigid geometry, local colors,

305
00:10:49,939 --> 00:10:53,057
and a restrained palette, muted overall

306
00:10:53,057 --> 00:10:54,641
with sharp accents

307
00:10:54,641 --> 00:10:56,225
guiding the viewer's eyes.

308
00:10:56,225 --> 00:10:59,310
Ancient virtue painted with absolute conviction.

309
00:10:59,310 --> 00:11:01,627
He had become exactly what Winckelmann

310
00:11:01,627 --> 00:11:03,278
the theorist had called for.

311
00:11:03,278 --> 00:11:05,412
He had become neoclassical.

312
00:11:05,412 --> 00:11:08,197
Worth noting, David wasn't alone in this.

313
00:11:08,197 --> 00:11:11,715
Across Europe, artists adopted the neoclassical style

314
00:11:11,715 --> 00:11:14,933
to explore ideas of beauty, harmony,

315
00:11:14,933 --> 00:11:16,100
and timeless order

316
00:11:16,100 --> 00:11:18,201
inspired by ancient Greece and Rome.

317
00:11:18,201 --> 00:11:21,119
Painters used classical myths and historical scenes

318
00:11:21,119 --> 00:11:24,521
to explore heroism, virtue, and human emotion.

319
00:11:24,521 --> 00:11:27,856
Sculptures like Canova focused on elegance

320
00:11:27,856 --> 00:11:31,107
of the human body, calm, idealized forms

321
00:11:31,107 --> 00:11:32,724
in perfect proportions.

322
00:11:32,724 --> 00:11:35,359
The style appeared in mythological paintings,

323
00:11:35,359 --> 00:11:38,327
portraits, architecture, decorative arts.

324
00:11:38,327 --> 00:11:39,961
It became a visual language

325
00:11:39,961 --> 00:11:41,712
of elegance and good taste.

326
00:11:41,712 --> 00:11:43,596
David worked in the same tradition

327
00:11:43,596 --> 00:11:45,730
as all of these artists, but what

328
00:11:45,730 --> 00:11:47,831
he did was charge the style

329
00:11:47,831 --> 00:11:50,099
with moral and political urgency,

330
00:11:50,099 --> 00:11:50,216
and

331
00:11:50,216 --> 00:11:52,316
you can see the difference immediately.

332
00:11:52,316 --> 00:11:54,317
His first big Salon success

333
00:11:54,317 --> 00:11:58,653
was Belisarius Begging for Alms in 1781.

334
00:11:58,653 --> 00:12:02,104
A Roman general, once great, now blind

335
00:12:02,104 --> 00:12:03,572
and begging in the street.

336
00:12:03,572 --> 00:12:04,889
The message?

337
00:12:04,889 --> 00:12:07,440
Even the greatest can be destroyed

338
00:12:07,440 --> 00:12:09,024
by an ungrateful state.

339
00:12:09,024 --> 00:12:09,874
People noticed.

340
00:12:09,874 --> 00:12:10,275
Success

341
00:12:10,275 --> 00:12:11,758
at the Salon made David

342
00:12:11,758 --> 00:12:14,160
a full member of the Académie Royale,

343
00:12:14,160 --> 00:12:16,477
the institute that trained French artists,

344
00:12:16,477 --> 00:12:17,811
set official standards,

345
00:12:17,811 --> 00:12:21,013
and decided what counted as serious painting.

346
00:12:21,013 --> 00:12:21,763
He became

347
00:12:21,763 --> 00:12:23,897
one of its most powerful teachers.

348
00:12:23,897 --> 00:12:25,715
His style, his values,

349
00:12:25,715 --> 00:12:27,682
his way of seeing passed

350
00:12:27,682 --> 00:12:30,017
directly into the next generation.

351
00:12:30,017 --> 00:12:32,701
He wasn't just working within the system,

352
00:12:32,701 --> 00:12:34,018
he was shaping it.

353
00:12:34,018 --> 00:12:34,752
But the painting

354
00:12:34,752 --> 00:12:37,220
that changed everything, the work

355
00:12:37,220 --> 00:12:41,305
that defined Neoclassicism came 3 years later.

356
00:12:41,305 --> 00:12:43,139
This is The Oath of the Horatii.

357
00:12:43,139 --> 00:12:46,591
David painted it in 1784.

358
00:12:46,591 --> 00:12:47,841
Take a moment

359
00:12:47,841 --> 00:12:49,442
and really look at it.

360
00:12:49,442 --> 00:12:51,510
3 brothers, the Horatii,

361
00:12:51,510 --> 00:12:52,743
are swearing an oath.

362
00:12:52,743 --> 00:12:54,744
They're about to fight to the death

363
00:12:54,744 --> 00:12:57,145
for Rome against 3 brothers

364
00:12:57,145 --> 00:12:58,463
for a rival city.

365
00:12:58,463 --> 00:13:00,380
Their father holds the swords.

366
00:13:00,380 --> 00:13:02,114
The brothers reach for them.

367
00:13:02,114 --> 00:13:06,516
Their bodies are taugh, geometric, almost architectural.

368
00:13:06,516 --> 00:13:08,200
They're not individuals.

369
00:13:08,200 --> 00:13:09,451
They're a machine,

370
00:13:09,451 --> 00:13:11,402
a machine built for duty.

371
00:13:11,402 --> 00:13:12,569
Look at the colors.

372
00:13:12,569 --> 00:13:15,937
The brothers wear brighter, more saturated reds.

373
00:13:15,937 --> 00:13:18,488
Your eye goes to them first,

374
00:13:18,488 --> 00:13:19,889
and it's supposed to.

375
00:13:19,889 --> 00:13:21,206
The women on the right

376
00:13:21,206 --> 00:13:24,658
are painted softer, muted tones, blues, grays,

377
00:13:24,658 --> 00:13:25,425
near white.

378
00:13:25,425 --> 00:13:26,909
The color itself tells you

379
00:13:26,909 --> 00:13:28,143
the moral structure

380
00:13:28,143 --> 00:13:31,044
before you even understood what's happening.

381
00:13:31,044 --> 00:13:33,428
Action and duty on the left, grief

382
00:13:33,428 --> 00:13:35,129
and passivity on the right.

383
00:13:35,129 --> 00:13:36,179
The stone background

384
00:13:36,179 --> 00:13:38,230
is all natural browns and grays,

385
00:13:38,230 --> 00:13:40,615
keeping your attention on the figures.

386
00:13:40,615 --> 00:13:43,099
The colors are clean, flat,

387
00:13:43,099 --> 00:13:44,783
and clearly separated.

388
00:13:44,783 --> 00:13:47,051
Every form is clear and deliberate.

389
00:13:47,051 --> 00:13:48,885
Notice also the light.

390
00:13:48,885 --> 00:13:52,637
Harsh, directional, almost theatrical,

391
00:13:52,637 --> 00:13:54,621
like a spotlight on a stage

392
00:13:54,621 --> 00:13:56,022
In the composition,

393
00:13:56,022 --> 00:13:58,156
your eye is drawn to the center,

394
00:13:58,156 --> 00:14:00,924
to the swords, the literal pivot point

395
00:14:00,924 --> 00:14:02,575
between duty and loss.

396
00:14:02,575 --> 00:14:04,826
The whole thing is controlled,

397
00:14:04,826 --> 00:14:08,427
deliberate, organized, the opposite of Rococo

398
00:14:08,427 --> 00:14:10,011
in every possible way.

399
00:14:10,011 --> 00:14:11,228
And then look at the right side

400
00:14:11,228 --> 00:14:13,163
of the painting, the woman.

401
00:14:13,163 --> 00:14:16,831
They're collapsed, weeping, because here's the thing.

402
00:14:16,831 --> 00:14:18,482
One of the Horatii brothers

403
00:14:18,482 --> 00:14:19,732
is married to a woman

404
00:14:19,732 --> 00:14:20,999
from the enemy city.

405
00:14:20,999 --> 00:14:22,884
She's actually the sister

406
00:14:22,884 --> 00:14:24,601
of one of the enemy brothers,

407
00:14:24,601 --> 00:14:26,719
and one of the enemy brothers

408
00:14:26,719 --> 00:14:28,753
is engaged to a Horatii sister.

409
00:14:28,753 --> 00:14:30,404
No matter who wins,

410
00:14:30,404 --> 00:14:32,871
these women lose someone they love.

411
00:14:32,871 --> 00:14:34,889
The men are rigid, vertical,

412
00:14:34,889 --> 00:14:36,373
all straight lines.

413
00:14:36,373 --> 00:14:39,641
The women are curved, soft, crumbling.

414
00:14:39,641 --> 00:14:41,609
Duty on the left, grief

415
00:14:41,609 --> 00:14:43,443
on the right, and the swords

416
00:14:43,443 --> 00:14:44,226
in the center.

417
00:14:44,226 --> 00:14:47,061
The message is brutal and clear.

418
00:14:47,061 --> 00:14:50,979
Duty to the state comes before everything,

419
00:14:50,979 --> 00:14:53,214
before love, before family,

420
00:14:53,214 --> 00:14:54,798
before your own life.

421
00:14:54,798 --> 00:14:56,432
When this painting was exhibited

422
00:14:56,432 --> 00:14:57,332
at the salon,

423
00:14:57,332 --> 00:14:59,183
people wept in front of it.

424
00:14:59,183 --> 00:15:01,434
Not just because it was sad,

425
00:15:01,434 --> 00:15:03,252
because it was powerful.

426
00:15:03,252 --> 00:15:05,069
It felt like a call to action.

427
00:15:05,069 --> 00:15:06,386
And David didn't stop.

428
00:15:06,386 --> 00:15:09,438
In 1780 7, The Death of Socrates.

429
00:15:09,438 --> 00:15:12,089
Socrates, condemned by the Athenian state

430
00:15:12,089 --> 00:15:13,073
for his ideas,

431
00:15:13,073 --> 00:15:13,506
calmly

432
00:15:13,506 --> 00:15:15,590
reaching for the cup of poison

433
00:15:15,590 --> 00:15:18,142
while his students fall apart around him.

434
00:15:18,142 --> 00:15:20,026
The state is killing him,

435
00:15:20,026 --> 00:15:22,994
and he accepts it with perfect calm.

436
00:15:22,994 --> 00:15:24,528
You die for what you believe.

437
00:15:24,528 --> 00:15:26,895
And then, in 1780 9,

438
00:15:26,895 --> 00:15:28,613
the lictors bring to Brutus

439
00:15:28,613 --> 00:15:29,713
the bodies of his sons.

440
00:15:29,713 --> 00:15:32,248
Brutus, the founder of the Roman Republic,

441
00:15:32,248 --> 00:15:33,999
has ordered the execution

442
00:15:33,999 --> 00:15:35,483
of his own sons

443
00:15:35,483 --> 00:15:37,950
for conspiring to restore the monarchy

444
00:15:37,950 --> 00:15:40,385
The bodies are being carried past him.

445
00:15:40,385 --> 00:15:41,585
He doesn't look.

446
00:15:41,585 --> 00:15:42,953
The women scream.

447
00:15:42,953 --> 00:15:44,437
He sits in shadow,

448
00:15:44,437 --> 00:15:47,138
rigid, destroyed, but unbroken.

449
00:15:47,138 --> 00:15:49,472
This painting was displayed at the Salon

450
00:15:49,472 --> 00:15:51,240
just weeks after the storming

451
00:15:51,240 --> 00:15:52,190
of the Bastille.

452
00:15:52,190 --> 00:15:53,958
The Paris prison was attacked

453
00:15:53,958 --> 00:15:55,875
in July 1789,

454
00:15:55,875 --> 00:15:58,626
marked the beginning of the French Revolution.

455
00:15:58,626 --> 00:16:00,911
The story goes that authorities tried

456
00:16:00,911 --> 00:16:02,495
to pull it from the exhibition,

457
00:16:02,495 --> 00:16:04,579
but the crowd demanded it to stay.

458
00:16:04,579 --> 00:16:05,546
whether that happened

459
00:16:05,546 --> 00:16:07,997
exactly as described is debated.

460
00:16:07,997 --> 00:16:09,615
Some historians think

461
00:16:09,615 --> 00:16:11,332
the tale was polished later

462
00:16:11,332 --> 00:16:14,133
to make David seem more heroically embattled.

463
00:16:14,133 --> 00:16:18,018
Regardless, the painting's timing was explosive.

464
00:16:18,018 --> 00:16:19,252
Do you see what's happening?

465
00:16:19,252 --> 00:16:21,503
These aren't just paintings anymore.

466
00:16:21,503 --> 00:16:22,904
A painting about a man

467
00:16:22,904 --> 00:16:24,038
who killed his sons

468
00:16:24,038 --> 00:16:26,572
to protect the Republic, displayed in Paris

469
00:16:26,572 --> 00:16:29,073
in summer of 1789?

470
00:16:29,073 --> 00:16:30,974
That's not art appreciation.

471
00:16:30,974 --> 00:16:33,258
That's a political statement, and

472
00:16:33,258 --> 00:16:34,792
everyone in that room knew it.

473
00:16:34,792 --> 00:16:36,210
David had spent a decade

474
00:16:36,210 --> 00:16:37,910
painting ancient heroes

475
00:16:37,910 --> 00:16:40,262
who sacrificed everything for the state,

476
00:16:40,262 --> 00:16:42,079
and now, in the summer of

477
00:16:42,079 --> 00:16:45,664
1789, the state was being torn apart

478
00:16:45,664 --> 00:16:46,631
and rebuilt.

479
00:16:46,631 --> 00:16:47,782
And David wasn't going

480
00:16:47,782 --> 00:16:48,999
to just paint it,

481
00:16:48,999 --> 00:16:51,166
he was going to join it.

482
00:16:51,166 --> 00:16:53,017
This is where the story goes dark,

483
00:16:53,017 --> 00:16:55,068
and I mean genuinely dark.

484
00:16:55,068 --> 00:16:57,336
Not art world drama dark.

485
00:16:57,336 --> 00:16:58,720
People dying dark.

486
00:16:58,720 --> 00:17:01,321
In 1792, David was elected

487
00:17:01,321 --> 00:17:04,889
to the National Convention, the revolutionary parliament.

488
00:17:04,889 --> 00:17:06,907
He didn't sit with the moderates.

489
00:17:06,907 --> 00:17:08,624
He sat with the Montagrats,

490
00:17:08,624 --> 00:17:10,825
the radicals, the Jacobins.

491
00:17:10,825 --> 00:17:11,492
They were led

492
00:17:11,492 --> 00:17:13,843
by Maximilian Robespierre, the lawyer

493
00:17:13,843 --> 00:17:16,361
who made himself the ideological heart

494
00:17:16,361 --> 00:17:17,311
of the revolution

495
00:17:17,311 --> 00:17:18,779
and who was rapidly becoming

496
00:17:18,779 --> 00:17:20,229
its most feared figure.

497
00:17:20,229 --> 00:17:23,181
And on January twenty-first, seventeen ninety-three,

498
00:17:23,181 --> 00:17:24,081
the day I mentioned

499
00:17:24,081 --> 00:17:24,948
at the beginning,

500
00:17:24,948 --> 00:17:25,748
David voted

501
00:17:25,748 --> 00:17:28,733
for the execution of King Louis XVI.

502
00:17:28,733 --> 00:17:32,085
A painter voted to kill a king.

503
00:17:32,085 --> 00:17:33,502
But he didn't stop there.

504
00:17:33,502 --> 00:17:37,670
David became essentially the revolution's visual authority.

505
00:17:37,670 --> 00:17:41,355
He organized festivals, massive public events meant

506
00:17:41,355 --> 00:17:44,957
to replace Catholic ritual with republican ceremony.

507
00:17:44,957 --> 00:17:47,208
He contributed to the design of uniforms

508
00:17:47,208 --> 00:17:48,592
and public imagery.

509
00:17:48,592 --> 00:17:50,209
He was deeply involved

510
00:17:50,209 --> 00:17:52,594
in shaping what the revolution looked like,

511
00:17:52,594 --> 00:17:55,078
and in a world before photography,

512
00:17:55,078 --> 00:17:56,445
before television,

513
00:17:56,445 --> 00:17:59,080
that meant he had real influence

514
00:17:59,080 --> 00:18:01,064
over what people believed about it.

515
00:18:01,064 --> 00:18:02,515
He was close to Robespierre,

516
00:18:02,515 --> 00:18:04,299
the radical Jacobin leader.

517
00:18:04,299 --> 00:18:05,550
Very close.

518
00:18:05,550 --> 00:18:07,267
He reportedly said to him,

519
00:18:07,267 --> 00:18:08,768
"If you drink hemlock,

520
00:18:08,768 --> 00:18:10,568
I will drink it with you."

521
00:18:10,568 --> 00:18:12,686
That's not a casual friendship.

522
00:18:12,686 --> 00:18:13,720
That's a pact.

523
00:18:13,720 --> 00:18:15,321
He was actively involved

524
00:18:15,321 --> 00:18:17,055
in the revolutionary government,

525
00:18:17,055 --> 00:18:19,773
sitting on the Committee of General Security,

526
00:18:19,773 --> 00:18:21,673
putting his name on documents

527
00:18:21,673 --> 00:18:25,492
that led to people being arrested, tried, and executed.

528
00:18:25,492 --> 00:18:25,825
was

529
00:18:25,825 --> 00:18:26,876
one of many people

530
00:18:26,876 --> 00:18:28,993
who signed, not acting alone,

531
00:18:28,993 --> 00:18:30,811
but consider what that means

532
00:18:30,811 --> 00:18:31,428
for the man

533
00:18:31,428 --> 00:18:33,429
who painted the death of Socrates.

534
00:18:33,429 --> 00:18:35,646
You remember that painting, Socrates

535
00:18:35,646 --> 00:18:36,830
in his last moments,

536
00:18:36,830 --> 00:18:39,098
calmly reaching for the cup of poison

537
00:18:39,098 --> 00:18:41,516
while his students fall apart around him?

538
00:18:41,516 --> 00:18:44,550
Socrates was condemned by the Athenian state

539
00:18:44,550 --> 00:18:47,151
for refusing to abandon his ideas.

540
00:18:47,151 --> 00:18:49,553
That's the subject David chose to paint

541
00:18:49,553 --> 00:18:50,836
and made beautiful,

542
00:18:50,836 --> 00:18:52,954
a man killed by the state.

543
00:18:52,954 --> 00:18:55,205
And now, David was the state.

544
00:18:55,205 --> 00:18:57,039
His name was on the paperwork.

545
00:18:57,039 --> 00:18:59,424
The tension between the ideals he painted

546
00:18:59,424 --> 00:19:02,492
and the reality he served is staggering.

547
00:19:02,492 --> 00:19:05,343
In July 1793, a shocking event

548
00:19:05,343 --> 00:19:07,727
in revolutionary Paris gave rise to

549
00:19:07,727 --> 00:19:10,195
one of the century's most famous paintings.

550
00:19:10,195 --> 00:19:13,130
Jean-Paul Marat was a revolutionary journalist,

551
00:19:13,130 --> 00:19:14,147
a radical.

552
00:19:14,147 --> 00:19:15,748
He had a skin condition

553
00:19:15,748 --> 00:19:17,548
that forced him to spend hours

554
00:19:17,548 --> 00:19:19,266
in a medicinal bath,

555
00:19:19,266 --> 00:19:21,300
where he would write, receive visitors,

556
00:19:21,300 --> 00:19:22,817
and conduct business.

557
00:19:22,817 --> 00:19:25,418
On July 13th, 1793,

558
00:19:25,418 --> 00:19:28,070
a young woman named Charlotte Corday

559
00:19:28,070 --> 00:19:29,837
talked her way into his apartment,

560
00:19:29,837 --> 00:19:34,689
claiming to have information about counter-revolutionary plots.

561
00:19:34,689 --> 00:19:35,840
Marat received her

562
00:19:35,840 --> 00:19:37,340
while sitting in his bath.

563
00:19:37,340 --> 00:19:38,908
She pulled out a knife

564
00:19:38,908 --> 00:19:40,892
and stabbed him in the chest.

565
00:19:40,892 --> 00:19:42,860
He died almost immediately.

566
00:19:42,860 --> 00:19:43,910
According to accounts

567
00:19:43,910 --> 00:19:45,311
that have been passed down,

568
00:19:45,311 --> 00:19:48,629
though some historians treat this with caution,

569
00:19:48,629 --> 00:19:50,230
David had visited Marat

570
00:19:50,230 --> 00:19:51,280
the day before.

571
00:19:51,280 --> 00:19:52,330
He knew the bath,

572
00:19:52,330 --> 00:19:53,898
the setup, the man,

573
00:19:53,898 --> 00:19:55,449
and when he heard the news,

574
00:19:55,449 --> 00:19:56,983
he went to work immediately.

575
00:19:56,983 --> 00:19:57,800
Look at it.

576
00:19:57,800 --> 00:19:59,717
Marat is slumped in his bath.

577
00:19:59,717 --> 00:20:01,501
His head is wrapped in a cloth.

578
00:20:01,501 --> 00:20:03,852
His skin is pale, almost glowing.

579
00:20:03,852 --> 00:20:06,270
His face is calm, peaceful.

580
00:20:06,270 --> 00:20:07,904
He looks like he's sleeping.

581
00:20:07,904 --> 00:20:09,572
He looks like Christ

582
00:20:09,572 --> 00:20:10,939
taken down from the cross.

583
00:20:10,939 --> 00:20:11,923
But I'll get to that

584
00:20:11,923 --> 00:20:12,423
in a sec.

585
00:20:12,431 --> 00:20:14,148
In his left hand, a letter.

586
00:20:14,148 --> 00:20:15,916
Corday, Marat's murderer,

587
00:20:15,916 --> 00:20:16,950
did use a letter

588
00:20:16,950 --> 00:20:18,450
to get into the apartment,

589
00:20:18,450 --> 00:20:20,385
but this isn't that letter.

590
00:20:20,385 --> 00:20:22,819
David wrote those words himself.

591
00:20:22,819 --> 00:20:23,436
They make

592
00:20:23,436 --> 00:20:25,170
Marat look like a man killed

593
00:20:25,170 --> 00:20:27,071
while helping someone in need.

594
00:20:27,071 --> 00:20:28,471
David put it in his hand

595
00:20:28,471 --> 00:20:30,522
on purpose as part of the myth

596
00:20:30,522 --> 00:20:31,356
he was building.

597
00:20:31,356 --> 00:20:33,524
On the floor, the knife, bloodied,

598
00:20:33,524 --> 00:20:35,224
and on the wooden block

599
00:20:35,224 --> 00:20:36,308
besides the bath,

600
00:20:36,308 --> 00:20:38,793
the block Marat used as a desk,

601
00:20:38,793 --> 00:20:40,477
David carved 2 words.

602
00:20:40,477 --> 00:20:42,828
To Marat from David.

603
00:20:42,828 --> 00:20:45,763
He signed the painting into the painting.

604
00:20:45,763 --> 00:20:48,264
It's a dedication, a memorial,

605
00:20:48,264 --> 00:20:49,598
and a political act.

606
00:20:49,598 --> 00:20:51,148
Now, here's what I need you

607
00:20:51,148 --> 00:20:52,149
to sit with.

608
00:20:52,149 --> 00:20:54,967
This painting is propaganda.

609
00:20:54,967 --> 00:20:56,434
It absolutely is.

610
00:20:56,434 --> 00:20:57,735
David has taken a man

611
00:20:57,735 --> 00:21:01,003
who was, by many accounts, paranoid, cruel,

612
00:21:01,003 --> 00:21:03,871
and responsive for stirring up mob violence

613
00:21:03,871 --> 00:21:06,105
And turned him into a saint.

614
00:21:06,105 --> 00:21:09,540
The bath is clean, the body idealized.

615
00:21:09,540 --> 00:21:12,124
The composition is borrowed directly

616
00:21:12,124 --> 00:21:15,476
from Christian art, specifically the Pietà,

617
00:21:15,476 --> 00:21:16,810
which is a famous image

618
00:21:16,810 --> 00:21:19,361
of Mary holding the body of Jesus.

619
00:21:19,361 --> 00:21:22,346
You know this Michelangelo's famous sculpture?

620
00:21:22,346 --> 00:21:24,246
Do you see it?

621
00:21:24,246 --> 00:21:28,281
That arrangement, that specific quality of grief

622
00:21:28,281 --> 00:21:30,199
held perfectly still.

623
00:21:30,199 --> 00:21:33,901
David took it and transplanted it into a bathtub in Paris.

624
00:21:33,901 --> 00:21:37,436
Marat as the Revolution's crucified Christ.

625
00:21:37,436 --> 00:21:38,836
David made this painting

626
00:21:38,836 --> 00:21:40,087
to serve the revolution,

627
00:21:40,087 --> 00:21:41,237
to turn a murderer

628
00:21:41,237 --> 00:21:42,238
into a martyr,

629
00:21:42,238 --> 00:21:42,655
to make

630
00:21:42,655 --> 00:21:46,990
you feel something specific, grief, outrage, devotion

631
00:21:46,990 --> 00:21:47,690
to the cause.

632
00:21:47,690 --> 00:21:50,541
It's propaganda and it's a masterpiece.

633
00:21:50,541 --> 00:21:53,026
Both are true at the same time,

634
00:21:53,026 --> 00:21:54,743
and that tension

635
00:21:54,743 --> 00:21:56,944
is what makes David so important

636
00:21:56,944 --> 00:21:58,362
and so unsettling.

637
00:21:58,362 --> 00:22:04,398
He painted virtue. He preached sacrifice. And he signed the warrants that sent people to die.

638
00:22:04,398 --> 00:22:08,283
The revolution gave David everything: power, purpose,

639
00:22:08,283 --> 00:22:09,633
a reason to paint

640
00:22:09,633 --> 00:22:11,101
Now, it was about

641
00:22:11,101 --> 00:22:12,251
to take it all back.

642
00:22:12,251 --> 00:22:13,485
It couldn't last.

643
00:22:13,485 --> 00:22:15,936
The revolution, like all revolutions,

644
00:22:15,936 --> 00:22:17,570
started eating its own.

645
00:22:17,570 --> 00:22:21,355
On July 27th, 1794, Robespierre,

646
00:22:21,355 --> 00:22:25,774
the radical Jacobin leader, was overthrown, arrested,

647
00:22:25,774 --> 00:22:28,575
executed the next day, and soon

648
00:22:28,575 --> 00:22:30,543
after, they came for David.

649
00:22:30,543 --> 00:22:32,443
He was arrested, imprisoned.

650
00:22:32,443 --> 00:22:33,994
He came very close

651
00:22:33,994 --> 00:22:37,095
to the guillotine himself, the same guillotine

652
00:22:37,095 --> 00:22:39,213
he had helped send others to.

653
00:22:39,213 --> 00:22:41,798
His students lobbied for his release.

654
00:22:41,798 --> 00:22:43,248
It took months.

655
00:22:43,248 --> 00:22:45,916
And in prison, he did something remarkable.

656
00:22:45,916 --> 00:22:48,617
He painted himself not as a hero,

657
00:22:48,617 --> 00:22:49,985
not as a martyr,

658
00:22:49,985 --> 00:22:52,169
not as someone Roman or Greek,

659
00:22:52,169 --> 00:22:53,586
just himself.

660
00:22:53,586 --> 00:22:56,387
A middle-aged man with a swollen cheek.

661
00:22:56,387 --> 00:22:57,788
he had a facial tumor

662
00:22:57,788 --> 00:22:59,656
that distorted his features.

663
00:22:59,656 --> 00:23:01,940
Holding a palette, looking out at you

664
00:23:01,940 --> 00:23:04,558
with an expression that's hard to read.

665
00:23:04,558 --> 00:23:05,725
Surprise?

666
00:23:05,725 --> 00:23:07,026
Confusion?

667
00:23:07,026 --> 00:23:07,976
Honesty?

668
00:23:07,976 --> 00:23:10,277
It might be the most intimate thing

669
00:23:10,277 --> 00:23:11,494
he ever painted

670
00:23:11,494 --> 00:23:13,879
because it wasn't for anyone.

671
00:23:13,879 --> 00:23:15,563
It wasn't for the salon

672
00:23:15,563 --> 00:23:17,080
or for the revolution.

673
00:23:17,080 --> 00:23:18,664
It was just a man

674
00:23:18,664 --> 00:23:21,082
in a cell looking at himself.

675
00:23:21,082 --> 00:23:21,999
And don't ask me

676
00:23:21,999 --> 00:23:24,833
how he got painting materials in prison.

677
00:23:24,833 --> 00:23:25,967
After his release,

678
00:23:25,967 --> 00:23:27,551
he said he had been deceived

679
00:23:27,551 --> 00:23:29,536
by the mask of patriotism.

680
00:23:29,536 --> 00:23:30,769
Was he?

681
00:23:30,769 --> 00:23:32,387
Was he really deceived,

682
00:23:32,387 --> 00:23:33,988
or was he just saying

683
00:23:33,988 --> 00:23:36,138
what he needed to say to survive?

684
00:23:36,138 --> 00:23:38,873
That's one of the great unanswerable questions

685
00:23:38,873 --> 00:23:41,324
about David, and I think

686
00:23:41,324 --> 00:23:42,825
the answer might be both.

687
00:23:42,825 --> 00:23:44,242
He was a true believer

688
00:23:44,242 --> 00:23:46,677
who was also very good in surviving.

689
00:23:46,677 --> 00:23:48,211
People are complicated.

690
00:23:48,211 --> 00:23:50,261
And then he met Napoleon.

691
00:23:50,261 --> 00:23:51,912
It was 1797.

692
00:23:51,912 --> 00:23:54,980
Napoleon was a young general, already famous,

693
00:23:54,980 --> 00:23:57,698
already radiating that kind of charisma

694
00:23:57,698 --> 00:24:00,249
that makes painter reach for their brushes.

695
00:24:00,249 --> 00:24:01,983
David met him and wrote,

696
00:24:01,983 --> 00:24:02,900
Oh, my friends,

697
00:24:02,900 --> 00:24:04,551
what a beautiful head he has.

698
00:24:04,551 --> 00:24:06,435
It is pure, it is great.

699
00:24:06,435 --> 00:24:08,670
It is as beautiful as the antique.

700
00:24:08,670 --> 00:24:10,337
As beautiful as the antique.

701
00:24:10,337 --> 00:24:11,621
There it is again.

702
00:24:11,621 --> 00:24:14,039
David looked at a living, breathing military

703
00:24:14,039 --> 00:24:16,707
commander and saw a Greek statue.

704
00:24:16,707 --> 00:24:17,907
He couldn't help himself.

705
00:24:17,907 --> 00:24:20,158
And Napoleon, a master of image

706
00:24:20,158 --> 00:24:22,259
and spectacle, saw in David

707
00:24:22,259 --> 00:24:24,043
exactly what he needed.

708
00:24:24,043 --> 00:24:26,678
The greatest painter of his time, ready

709
00:24:26,678 --> 00:24:28,995
to turn him into a living legend.

710
00:24:28,995 --> 00:24:32,080
Okay.Napoleon crossing the Alps, 1801.

711
00:24:32,080 --> 00:24:33,848
You know this image.

712
00:24:33,848 --> 00:24:34,665
Even if

713
00:24:34,665 --> 00:24:37,149
you never been into an art museum,

714
00:24:37,149 --> 00:24:38,800
you know this image.

715
00:24:38,800 --> 00:24:40,167
Napoleon on a rearing

716
00:24:40,167 --> 00:24:43,168
white horse, cape flowing, arm pointing

717
00:24:43,168 --> 00:24:46,737
forward, the names of Hannibal and Charlemagne

718
00:24:46,737 --> 00:24:48,671
carved into the rocks below him,

719
00:24:48,671 --> 00:24:49,655
As if to say

720
00:24:49,655 --> 00:24:51,355
he belongs among them.

721
00:24:51,355 --> 00:24:53,189
I've seen this painting in person,

722
00:24:53,189 --> 00:24:54,423
and the first thing

723
00:24:54,423 --> 00:24:56,024
that hits you is the scale.

724
00:24:56,024 --> 00:24:57,425
If you see it on a screen,

725
00:24:57,425 --> 00:25:00,193
it's completely different from how

726
00:25:00,193 --> 00:25:02,360
people back at the time felt when

727
00:25:02,360 --> 00:25:04,611
they saw it in front of them.

728
00:25:04,611 --> 00:25:07,679
Like, this painting is about this size,

729
00:25:07,679 --> 00:25:08,363
you just stand

730
00:25:08,363 --> 00:25:10,180
in front of it, and you feel

731
00:25:10,180 --> 00:25:12,081
that you're looking at something amazing.

732
00:25:12,081 --> 00:25:13,232
I can't explain it.

733
00:25:13,232 --> 00:25:14,699
You, you have to experience it,

734
00:25:14,699 --> 00:25:16,667
'cause I was really surprised

735
00:25:16,667 --> 00:25:17,567
to feel that way.

736
00:25:17,567 --> 00:25:18,984
Okay, back to the story.

737
00:25:18,984 --> 00:25:20,468
The painting is huge.

738
00:25:20,468 --> 00:25:22,286
You stand in front of it, and

739
00:25:22,286 --> 00:25:24,720
you feel small, which is, of course,

740
00:25:24,720 --> 00:25:25,921
exactly the point.

741
00:25:25,921 --> 00:25:26,421
Napoleon

742
00:25:26,421 --> 00:25:28,288
asked to be painted calm

743
00:25:28,288 --> 00:25:29,739
on a spirited horse.

744
00:25:29,739 --> 00:25:31,140
David delivered.

745
00:25:31,140 --> 00:25:32,290
Here's the thing, though.

746
00:25:32,290 --> 00:25:34,925
The real crossing was difficult, cold,

747
00:25:34,925 --> 00:25:36,709
and unglamorous.

748
00:25:36,709 --> 00:25:38,893
Napoleon rode a mule for much

749
00:25:38,893 --> 00:25:40,944
of it, led by a local guide.

750
00:25:40,944 --> 00:25:43,462
David wasn't painting what happened.

751
00:25:43,462 --> 00:25:44,312
He was painting

752
00:25:44,312 --> 00:25:47,364
what Napoleon wanted to believe about himself.

753
00:25:47,364 --> 00:25:49,014
The heroic version.

754
00:25:49,014 --> 00:25:49,598
The myth.

755
00:25:49,598 --> 00:25:51,432
Nobody remembers the mule.

756
00:25:51,432 --> 00:25:53,316
Everyone remembers this.

757
00:25:53,316 --> 00:25:55,034
And then there's the coronation.

758
00:25:55,034 --> 00:25:57,435
1805 to 1807.

759
00:25:57,435 --> 00:25:59,552
Over 30 feet wide.

760
00:25:59,552 --> 00:26:02,921
Napoleon crowning Josephine at Notre Dame,

761
00:26:02,921 --> 00:26:05,205
surrounded by hundreds of figures.

762
00:26:05,205 --> 00:26:06,839
David was there in person,

763
00:26:06,839 --> 00:26:08,056
sketching the ceremony.

764
00:26:08,056 --> 00:26:10,307
But he rearranged reality.

765
00:26:10,307 --> 00:26:13,225
Look, see that woman in the balcony?

766
00:26:13,225 --> 00:26:15,860
That's Napoleon's mother, Leticia.

767
00:26:15,860 --> 00:26:19,495
She's prominently placed, watching proudly.

768
00:26:19,495 --> 00:26:22,179
Except she wasn't there.

769
00:26:22,179 --> 00:26:23,780
She refused to come.

770
00:26:23,780 --> 00:26:26,164
David painted her in anyway

771
00:26:26,164 --> 00:26:28,499
because Napoleon wanted her there.

772
00:26:28,499 --> 00:26:30,166
The painting isn't a record

773
00:26:30,166 --> 00:26:31,417
of what happened.

774
00:26:31,417 --> 00:26:32,367
It's a record

775
00:26:32,367 --> 00:26:34,218
of what should have happened

776
00:26:34,218 --> 00:26:35,869
According to the man in charge.

777
00:26:35,869 --> 00:26:38,920
After Napoleon's final defeat in 1815,

778
00:26:38,920 --> 00:26:41,138
the Bourbon monarchy was restored, and

779
00:26:41,138 --> 00:26:43,155
they had a long memory.

780
00:26:43,155 --> 00:26:45,490
David had voted to execute their king

781
00:26:45,490 --> 00:26:47,040
in 1793.

782
00:26:47,040 --> 00:26:49,458
That was 22 years ago.

783
00:26:49,458 --> 00:26:51,059
They hadn't forgotten.

784
00:26:51,059 --> 00:26:53,193
He was exiled, banned from France

785
00:26:53,193 --> 00:26:54,293
as a king killer.

786
00:26:54,293 --> 00:26:56,695
He moved to Brussels and kept painting,

787
00:26:56,695 --> 00:26:59,879
but the work got softer, less urgent.

788
00:26:59,879 --> 00:27:01,530
The fire was going out.

789
00:27:01,530 --> 00:27:02,581
He died in Brussels

790
00:27:02,581 --> 00:27:05,398
on December 29th, 1825,

791
00:27:05,398 --> 00:27:07,116
at the age of 77.

792
00:27:07,116 --> 00:27:07,983
France refused

793
00:27:07,983 --> 00:27:09,600
to allow his body to return.

794
00:27:09,600 --> 00:27:10,467
The man who had

795
00:27:10,467 --> 00:27:12,201
been the most powerful artist

796
00:27:12,201 --> 00:27:13,252
in the country,

797
00:27:13,252 --> 00:27:15,270
who had shaped the visual identity

798
00:27:15,270 --> 00:27:17,354
of the revolution, of Napoleon,

799
00:27:17,354 --> 00:27:19,005
of an entire era,

800
00:27:19,005 --> 00:27:21,155
was buried in a foreign city.

801
00:27:21,155 --> 00:27:22,406
He's still there.

802
00:27:22,406 --> 00:27:23,440
So, what did

803
00:27:23,440 --> 00:27:24,840
David leave behind?

804
00:27:24,840 --> 00:27:27,792
A movement, a set of rules,

805
00:27:27,792 --> 00:27:30,426
and an institution, the Académie Royale,

806
00:27:30,426 --> 00:27:32,444
that would enforce those rules

807
00:27:32,444 --> 00:27:34,411
for the next 50 years.

808
00:27:34,411 --> 00:27:36,045
His greatest student, Ingres,

809
00:27:36,045 --> 00:27:38,597
became the guardian of that legacy.

810
00:27:38,597 --> 00:27:40,531
He spent his entire career

811
00:27:40,531 --> 00:27:44,032
defending classical drawing, insisting that discipline

812
00:27:44,032 --> 00:27:46,784
and line were the foundation of everything.

813
00:27:46,784 --> 00:27:48,334
The Académie backed him.

814
00:27:48,334 --> 00:27:50,785
For decades, the world David built held.

815
00:27:50,785 --> 00:27:51,836
So here's

816
00:27:51,836 --> 00:27:53,153
where I want to leave you.

817
00:27:53,153 --> 00:27:56,688
David understood something fundamental about images.

818
00:27:56,688 --> 00:27:59,923
They aren't just decoration, they're arguments.

819
00:27:59,923 --> 00:28:02,224
A painting can make you believe something.

820
00:28:02,224 --> 00:28:03,408
It can make an idea

821
00:28:03,408 --> 00:28:06,276
feel noble, inevitable, even heroic.

822
00:28:06,276 --> 00:28:06,926
his style

823
00:28:06,926 --> 00:28:09,177
helped make that power possible

824
00:28:09,177 --> 00:28:12,095
The clean lines, the stark compositions,

825
00:28:12,095 --> 00:28:14,479
the restrained, controlled color.

826
00:28:14,479 --> 00:28:17,814
Everything is clear, deliberate, and serious.

827
00:28:17,814 --> 00:28:19,615
Nothing is accidental.

828
00:28:19,615 --> 00:28:21,699
The paintings feel certain

829
00:28:21,699 --> 00:28:23,183
about what they are saying,

830
00:28:23,183 --> 00:28:25,584
and that certainty is persuasive.

831
00:28:25,584 --> 00:28:28,169
And the images themself did real work.

832
00:28:28,169 --> 00:28:29,853
The Oath of the Horatii

833
00:28:29,853 --> 00:28:31,870
didn't just show Roman virtue,

834
00:28:31,870 --> 00:28:33,304
it presented a model

835
00:28:33,304 --> 00:28:35,172
of duty and sacrifice.

836
00:28:35,172 --> 00:28:37,590
The Death of Marat didn't simply show

837
00:28:37,590 --> 00:28:39,991
a political killing, it transformed Marat

838
00:28:39,991 --> 00:28:41,791
into a martyr of the revolution.

839
00:28:41,791 --> 00:28:43,342
Napoleon crossing the Alps

840
00:28:43,342 --> 00:28:47,994
didn't document an event. It constructed Napoleon's image of leadership.

841
00:28:47,994 --> 00:28:57,632
That’s David’s real legacy. Not just a style, and not only a school of followers but a demonstration of how powerful images can shape political imagination.

842
00:28:57,632 --> 00:28:59,333
But the more interesting part

843
00:28:59,333 --> 00:29:01,600
of David's story isn't the propaganda,

844
00:29:01,600 --> 00:29:03,118
it's the man behind it.

845
00:29:03,118 --> 00:29:06,269
David painted virtue, duty, and sacrifice,

846
00:29:06,269 --> 00:29:08,887
and he seemed to have genuinely believe

847
00:29:08,887 --> 00:29:10,237
in those ideals.

848
00:29:10,237 --> 00:29:11,621
At the same time,

849
00:29:11,621 --> 00:29:13,656
he lived at the center of power

850
00:29:13,656 --> 00:29:15,807
during one of the most violent

851
00:29:15,807 --> 00:29:18,191
and chaotic periods in French history.

852
00:29:18,191 --> 00:29:19,992
That combination was rare.

853
00:29:19,992 --> 00:29:22,860
An artist who wasn't just observing events,

854
00:29:22,860 --> 00:29:24,644
but helping shape how

855
00:29:24,644 --> 00:29:26,161
they were seen and remembered.

856
00:29:26,161 --> 00:29:27,212
And that may be

857
00:29:27,212 --> 00:29:29,346
what makes him so remarkable.

858
00:29:29,346 --> 00:29:31,063
Not just a great painter,

859
00:29:31,063 --> 00:29:32,281
but an artist

860
00:29:32,281 --> 00:29:34,715
whose images helped define an era.

861
00:29:34,715 --> 00:29:36,282
But not everyone accepted

862
00:29:36,282 --> 00:29:37,666
what David had built

863
00:29:37,666 --> 00:29:39,934
Not everyone thought paintings

864
00:29:39,934 --> 00:29:41,635
should be lessons in virtue

865
00:29:41,635 --> 00:29:43,919
or that reason should rule everything art

866
00:29:43,919 --> 00:29:44,353
could be.

867
00:29:44,353 --> 00:29:47,171
One painter born in seventeen ninety-eight,

868
00:29:47,171 --> 00:29:49,472
just a few years after the Terror,

869
00:29:49,472 --> 00:29:52,273
the revolution's most violent period,

870
00:29:52,273 --> 00:29:52,756
was about

871
00:29:52,756 --> 00:29:54,440
to blow the whole thing up.

872
00:29:54,440 --> 00:29:56,408
Was about to blow the whole thing

873
00:29:56,408 --> 00:29:59,243
up with color, with chaos,

874
00:29:59,243 --> 00:30:01,093
with a trip to North Africa

875
00:30:01,093 --> 00:30:03,044
that changed the way he saw everything.

876
00:30:03,044 --> 00:30:05,329
His name was Eugène Delacroix,

877
00:30:05,329 --> 00:30:06,479
and his story starts

878
00:30:06,479 --> 00:30:09,180
with a shipwreck, a madman,

879
00:30:09,180 --> 00:30:11,615
and a raft full of corpses.

880
00:30:11,615 --> 00:30:13,082
That's next time.

881
00:30:13,082 --> 00:30:14,016
ביי.
